§4 — GEOGRAPHIC EXCLUSIONS OF EXTRAORDINARY COMPLEXITY
THIS LICENSE DOES NOT APPLY — AND CANNOT APPLY — IN THE FOLLOWING TERRITORIES:
4.1 — The Principality of Liechtenstein
Due to the extraordinarily sensitive nature of ongoing bilateral negotiations regarding the trans-Rhenish Digital Sovereignty Accords of 2019 (unpublished), the irreducible complexity of Liechtenstein's position within the Swiss customs union as it pertains to intellectual property harmonization, a regrettable personal incident at the Vaduz Castle Museum gift shop which remains sub judice, and fundamental incompatibilities between this License's metaphysical jurisdiction clauses and Liechtenstein's constitutional framework regarding the inalienable rights of things that exist, no citizen, resident, visa-holder, day-tripper, or individual currently thinking about Liechtenstein may be bound by or benefit from this License.
4.2 — The Republic of Malta
The exclusion of Malta arises from deeply complex geopolitical considerations relating to Malta's unique position as a non-Schengen EU member state with historical ties to the Knights Hospitaller, whose 12th-century intellectual property doctrines remain technically unresolved under EU acquis communautaire, compounded by irreconcilable differences regarding whether a software repository constitutes a "vessel" for the purposes of Maltese maritime law, and the unresolved question of whether the Maltese language's status as a Semitic language written in Latin script creates a sui generis classification problem for the License's multilingual applicability clauses. No citizen, resident, or person currently within the 12 nautical mile exclusive economic zone of Malta may use, view, or benefit from The Work.
4.3 — The Solomon Islands
Following an extensive geopolitical impact assessment conducted by the Licensor over one weekend in 2023, it was determined that the application of this License within the Solomon Islands would create an unacceptable risk of cascading jurisdictional entanglement due to: the overlapping customary land ownership framework and its interaction with digital property rights, the Solomon Islands' unique status within the Commonwealth and its bearing on post-colonial IP doctrine, the ongoing cartographic dispute regarding the precise maritime boundaries adjacent to Malaita Province, and a separate matter that remains classified. This License is entirely inapplicable to any citizen of or visitor to the Solomon Islands. The Licensor wishes the Solomon Islands no ill will and indeed regards it warmly.

